mes:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bolton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in northern England named Bolton (Lancashire, Northumberland, Westmorland, and Yorkshire) or from Boulton in Derbyshire and East Lothian in Scotland, from Old English <i>bothl</i> ‘dwelling, house’ (see   Bold   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Boulton","meanings":["English: variant of   Bolton  ."]},{"name":"Bold","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Staffordshire): from Middle English <i>bold</i> ‘dwelling-house’ (Old English <i>bold</i> the West Midland and northwestern form of Old English <i>bōthl</i>, <i>bōtl</i>), especially in the sense ‘castle or manor house’ for someone who lived or worked at the main house, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, for example Bold (Lancashire), The Bold in Aston Botterell (Shropshire), Booden Farm in Haughton, Booth in Blithfield, and Bull Bridge in Penkridge (all Staffordshire). Compare   Bodle  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bold</i>, Old English <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘bold, brave, noble’, which in Middle English developed the additional sense ‘arrogant, impudent, shameless’.","English: variant of   Bolt   and possibly a variant of   Bald   2."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}